Project Overview

In this project, I will practice the visualization skills with two datasets to capture the temporal and spatial patterns.

Datasets

  • Part 1. The UFO Sightings Data
  • Part 2. The Hospital Location Data

Find the _data folder, then read the datasets using the correct R command.

Part 1. The UFO Sightings Data

This data contains over 80,000 reports of UFO sightings over the last century in six major countries (and other places). You can learn more about this data by checking: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/NUFORC/ufo-sightings.

  1. Read and Describe the Data

    What is the dimension of the data? What do the columns mean? What is the unit of observation?

    Dimensions of the data: Row - 88875 cols - 12

    The meaning of each column:

    datetime: The date and time of the UFO sighting.

    city: The city where the UFO sighting was reported.

    state: The state where the UFO sighting was reported.

    country: The country where the UFO sighting was reported.

    shape: The shape of the UFO as described in the report.

    duration..seconds.: The duration of the UFO sighting in seconds.

    duration..hours.min.: The duration of the UFO sighting in hours and minutes.

    comments: Additional comments or details about the UFO sighting.

    date.posted: The date when the UFO sighting report was posted.

    latitude: The latitude coordinate of the UFO sighting location.

    longitude: The longitude coordinate of the UFO sighting location.

    The unit of observation in this dataset is each individual UFO sighting event

  2. Please plot a temporal/time-series graph to present the following patterns. You may need to subset or mutate the data for graphing.

    (1) the total number of UFO sighting reports over the years (date_break = year). 

    #type of your code/command here.
   ufo_data$datetime <-
  as.Date(ufo_data$datetime, format = "%m/%d/%Y") 

ufo_data <- ufo_data |>
  mutate(Year = as.integer(format(datetime, "%Y")),# Extract the Year from datetime;
         Month = as.integer(format(datetime, "%m")),
         Day = as.integer(format(datetime, "%d")))

head(ufo_data) 
      UFO_year <- ufo_data |>
  group_by(Year) |>                           
  mutate(YearSum = n())|>
  ggplot(aes(x = as.Date(Year), y = YearSum))+
  geom_line()+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1906, 2015, by = 5))+ 
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1))+
  xlab("Year")+
  ylab("Number of UFO sighting reports")

UFO_year

    (2) the total number of UFO sighting reports by months between 2010-01-01 and 2014-01-01. 

     ufo_data |>
  group_by(Year, Month) |>  
  summarise(MonthSum = n())|>
  mutate(UniqueMonth = make_date(Year, Month)) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = UniqueMonth, y = MonthSum))+
  geom_line()+
  scale_x_date(limits = as.Date(c("2010-01-01", "2014-01-01")), date_breaks = "1 month", date_labels = "%b %Y") + 
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1)) +
  xlab("Month")+
  ylab("Number of UFO Sighting Reports by Months")
    `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Year'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.
    Warning: Removed 778 rows containing missing values (`geom_line()`).

  3. Please write a paragraph describing the patterns you find on the two graphs above.

    Answers: From the total number of sightings over the years graph, we could see that the graph is left skewed meaning maximum data lies on the right side of the plot. Hence, we can conclude that the number of UFO sightings increases from 2000. Moreover, we see that UFO sighting reports significantly increases after 1995. Further, there was huge increase after 2010. The possible reasons could be due to development of mass media, advancement in internet, mobile devices etc. making normal individual to report such sightings.

    Now, looking at number of ufo sightings vs months plot is that it follows almost normal/bell curve per year, i.e., the maximum sighting are reported during month of June, July and August for each year (one possible reason is that this is stargazing season in Northern Hemisphere) and it was lowest in the month of February for each year. Also, the monthly plot of year 2012 and 2013 have higher monthly distribution then years 2010 and 2011, explaining the highest overall count among all year.

    Overall, both graphs highlight the temporal patterns and fluctuations in UFO sighting reports, offering intriguing insights into the dynamics of UFO phenomena over time and within specific timeframes.

Part 2. The Hospital Location Data

This data contains the locations of hospitals in the United States. You can learn more about this data by checking: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/andrewmvd/us-hospital-locations

  1. Read and Describe the Data

    What is the dimension of the data? What do the columns mean? What is the unit of observation?

    Dimensions of the data: Row - 7596 cols - 15

    Each column represents-

    ID: Unique identifier for each hospital.

    NAME: Name of the hospital.

    ADDRESS: Street address of the hospital.

    CITY: City where the hospital is located.

    STATE: State where the hospital is located.

    ZIP: ZIP code of the hospitalâs location.

    TYPE: Type of hospital (e.g., General Acute Care).

    STATUS: Status of the hospital (e.g., Open, Closed).

    POPULATION: Population served by the hospital.

    COUNTY: County where the hospital is located.

    COUNTRY: Country where the hospital is located.

    LATITUDE: Latitude coordinate of the hospitalâs location.

    LONGITUDE: Longitude coordinate of the hospitalâs location.

    OWNER: Owner of the hospital.

    BEDS: Number of beds available in the hospital.

    The unit of observation in this dataset is each row, which represents a different hospital.

  theme_minimal()

  4. Please write a paragraph describing the pattern of the hospital locations you find on the map above.

    Answer: The map above displays hospital locations across the United States, with open hospitals marked in skyblue and closed hospitals in purple. Upon examining the pattern of hospital locations, several observations can be made. Firstly, there is a noticeable concentration of hospitals in urban areas, particularly in major cities and metropolitan regions. This concentration aligns with population centers where healthcare demand is typically higher. Additionally, clusters of hospitals are often found along major highways and transportation routes, indicating strategic placement for accessibility and emergency services. In contrast, rural and remote areas show fewer hospital locations, reflecting challenges in healthcare access faced by these communities. The distribution of open and closed hospitals also reveals insights into healthcare infrastructure dynamics, with closures often seen in areas experiencing demographic shifts or economic challenges. Overall, the map offers a glimpse into the spatial distribution of healthcare facilities in the United States, highlighting areas of healthcare accessibility and potential disparities.
